Yes, we can accumulate errors for each file and then combine them at the end.  I'm thinking something like this:

```
std::vector<std::string> errors;
for (const std::string& filename : *crl_files) {
  std::string path = absl::StrCat(directory, '/', filename);
  auto crl = ReadCrlFromFile(path);
  if (!crl.ok()) {
    errors.push_back(absl::StrCat(path, ": ", crl.status().ToString()));
    continue;
  }
  // ...
}
if (!errors.empty()) {
  absl::Status status = absl::InvalidArgumentError(
      absl::StrCat("errors reading CRL directory: [", absl::StrJoin(errors, "; "), "]"));
}
```

One thing to consider here is what status code you should use for the combined error.  It's not clear to me that INVALID_ARGUMENT is the right code here.  What if there's a filesystem I/O error reading the file (i.e., the machine has a bad disk)?  That would be a completely different error code.

The simple thing to do here is probably to just use code UNKNOWN.  I suppose you could try to be smarter by checking the code from the individual errors and using that if they all happen to be the same code, but if different files have different status codes, you don't really have any way of knowing which one to use.  And it's probably overkill to even try to be that smart.

